\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 An experimental procedure known as the precuing technique, popularized in the early 1980s by Rosenbaum (1980, 1983), has been commonly used to investigate this relationship. In this }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 procedure, researchers provide participants with differing amounts of advance information about which response must\u8239 ?
be made in a choice situation. In Rosenbaum\rquote s experiments, participants had to move a }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 hand}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3
 as quickly as possible to hit a signaled target key. There were three response dimensions, all of which involved a two-choice situation: the }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3 arm}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  to move (left or right); the }{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3
direction}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  to move (away from or toward th}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 e b}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 ody); and the }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3 extent}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  of the movement (short or long). Prior to the signal to move, the \u173 ?
participants could receive advance information (i.e., the \u173 ?precue) specifying the correct upcoming response for none, one, two, or all three of the dimensions. The results showed that as the number of precued \u173 ?
dimensions increased, the RT decreased. The benefit of the advance information was that participants would need to prepare only the remaining non-precued dimensions after the \ldblquote go}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \rdblquote  \u173 ?signal. \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 An important finding about the effect of a \u173 ?
precue on the time required to prepare an action is that the person must maintain his or her attention to the location of the advance information until the actual \u173 ?
signal to move occurs. Eversheim and Bock (2002) showed in a series of experiments that when a \u173 ?person\rquote s attention was diverted by some other \u173 ?
activity between the precue and the signal to move, the person lost the RT benefit of the advance \u173 ?information.\par }\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 The Influence of the Probability \line of Precue Correctness}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 An interesting twist to the precuing situation occurs \line when the advance information may or may not be correct. The critical factor influencing preparation time in this situation is the }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3 probability}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  of the advance information\rquote s correctness. For example, if a basketball player is defending one-on-one against a player with the ball and knows that the player must either shoot or pass the ball, the defensive player has a 50\'d050 chance of guessing what the offensive player will do and preparing an appropriate action. But, if the defensive player knows that when the \u173 ?
offensive player is at that specific location on the\u8239 ?court, he or she will pass the ball 80 percent of the time, the defensive player will in all likelihood \u173 ?
begin to prepare to defend against the player passing the ball. In this situation, the advance information (i.e., the precue) provides the defensive player with an option that is better than 50\'d050. As a result, especially with only a 20 percent chance of making the wrong choice, the defensive player would \u173 ?
probably }{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3 bias}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  his or her action preparation to defend against the player passing the ball.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 What advantage would the defensive player gain by biasing his or her preparation in this way? Would it be possible that this preparation bias might be a disadvantage? The }
{\fs20 answers}{\fs20  to these questions depend on whether the defensive player is correct or not in biasing his or her preparation. Research in laboratory settings provides evidence that shows the }
{\fs20 advantages and disadvantages}{\fs20  that can occur in situations like this one. The best example is an experiment by}{\fs20
 }{\fs20 Larish and Stelmach (1982), which has become the model approach to study this issue. Participants received advance information about whether the right hand or}
{\fs20  }{\fs20 the left hand should hit the target. But this information was correct only 20 percent, 50 percent, }{\fs20 \line }
{\fs20 or 80 percent of the time. The results (shown in }{\fs20 figure}{\fs20  }{\fs20 8.2) illustrate the }{\*\cs63\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw0
cost-benefit trade-off}{\fs20  \u173 ?}{\fs20 \line }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 associated with this situation. When there was a \u173 ?
50\'d050 chance (50 percent correct condition) of the precue\rquote s being correct, participants responded as }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4
if the task were a two-choice RT task. However, in the 80\'d020 condition, participants obviously biased their \u173 ?responses to move in the direction of the precued \u173 ?
target. When they were correct, there was a benefit; their RTs were }{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd1\expndtw4 faster}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4
 than if they had not biased their responses. However, when they were wrong (the 20 percent case), there was a cost: their RT was }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd1\expndtw4 slower}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4  than it was in the 50\'d050 condition.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \par }
\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Stimulus-Response Compatibility\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 Another task characteristic that influences the movement preparation time is the physical relationship between the stimulus and response choices. The study of what is termed }
{\*\cs63\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw1 stimulus-response \line }{\*\cs63\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 (S-R) compatibility}{\fs20  has a long history that dates back to World War II (for a discussion of this history, see Proctor & Reeve, 1990, or Proctor, Vu, & Pick, 2005). This extensive study has shown consistently that }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i RT will be faster as the relationship between the stimulus characteristics and their }{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2
required response becomes more compatible.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  }{\fs20 Conversely, RT will be slower as this relationship becomes less compatible.\par }
\pard\plain \s17\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb260\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs66\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Spatial relationship effects.}
{\fs20 \u8194\'20The spatial relationship between the stimulus and response devices is the most common way of considering stimulus-\u173 ?
response compatibility. For example, suppose a person has to push one of three keys in response to the illumination of one of three lights. If the lights and keys are arranged horizontally with the key to be pushed located under the light indicating that \u173 ?
response, then the situation is more compatible than if the lights are vertical and the buttons are horizontal. A more compatible relationship would lead to faster RTs (and fewer errors) than a less compatible situation.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s17\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb244\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs66\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw2\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 The Stroop effect.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2
\u8194\'20A different type of S-R compatibility situation occurs when the appearance of the stimulus suggests one type of response, but the \u173 ?
situation requires a different response. The best example of this is the }{\*\cs63\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw2 Stroop effect}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2
, which is a \u173 ?phenomenon that occurs when a person must verbally respond to the ink color of a word that names a color. This phenomenon is named after J. R. Stroop who first reported it (Stroop, 1935). When the word name and ink color of the word are the same, RT is faster than if the word is a different color than its name. For example, if BLUE is the word, people will say }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \ldblquote blue\rdblquote  faster when the ink color is blue than when the word name is RED but\u8239 ?the ink color is blue. In terms of stimulus-\line \u173 ?
response compatibility, a compatible situation \u173 ?exists when the ink color of a word is the same as\u8239 ?the color it names and the person must say the ink color; but an\u8239 ?
incompatible situation exists when the word is written in a color that is different from the one it names and the person must say the ink color.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \par }\pard\plain \s17\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3 Why does S-R compatability affect RT?}{\*\cs67\f5\fs18\caps0\scaps0\b\i0\ul0\strike0\expnd1\expndtw3\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0
\u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3 To account for the effect of stimulus-response compatibility on RT, Zelaznik and Franz (1990) presented evidence showing that when S-R compatibility is low, RT increases are due to }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i response \u173 ?selection}{\fs20  problems. On the other hand, when S-R }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 compatibility is high, response selection processing }
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3 is minimal, so that any RT changes reflect motor processes related to preparation of the selected }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0
response. Weeks and Proctor (1990) further }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3 de\u173 ?\u173 ?veloped this point by demonstrating that the \u173 ?
\line specific response selection problem is due to translation problems involving the mapping of the stimulus \u173 ?locations to the response locations. Because this translation process requires }
{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd1\expndtw3 additional }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3 time, RT increases.\par }\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Foreperiod Length Regularity}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 A part of the preparation process begins when a person detects a signal indicating that the signal to respond will occur shortly. The interval between this \ldblquote warning\rdblquote  signal and the stimulus, or \ldblquote go\rdblquote  \u173 ?
signal, \line is known as the }{\*\cs63\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 foreperiod}{\fs20 . In simple-RT situ-ations, the regularity of the length of this interval \line influences RT. If the foreperiod is a constant length, that is, the same amount of time for every trial, RT will be shorter than it would be if the length of the foreperiod varies.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 We can attribute the shorter RT associated \line with constant foreperiods to }{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 anticipation}
{\fs20  by the \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 performer. Because it is a simple-RT situation, the person knows before the warning signal what response will be required. And because every trial has the same foreperiod length, he or she knows when the go signal will occur after the warning \u173 ?
signal. As a result, the person can prepare the required action in advance of the go signal}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
and initiate it very close to}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  the go signal.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 The starts of sprint races in track or swimming \u173 ?
illustrate the need to implement an understanding of the effect on RT of a constant foreperiod length. If the starter of these races maintains a constant amount of time between his or her signal for the athletes to get ready and the gun or sound to start running or swimming, the athletes can anticipate the go signal and gain an unfair advantage over other athletes who did not anticipate the signal as accurately. We would \u173 ?
expect some variation in the actual initiations of movement because people vary in terms of their \u173 ?capability to time the precise amounts of time typically involved in the RT foreperiods of sprint starts. }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Interestingly, sprinters are charged a false start if their reaction time out of the blocks is less than 10}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 0 m}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 sec. Because the processing of the sound from the starter}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3
\rquote }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 s gun and the preparation and initiation of the start are thought to take at least 100 msec, a RT less than 100 msec is considered to have resulted from anticipation (Lee, 2011).}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \par }\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Movement Complexity}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 Movement complexity is }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 typically}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5  based on the number of parts to a movement. Research evidence demonstrating the effect of movement complexity on RT was \u173 ?
reported primarily in the 1960s through the early 1980s, beginning with the now-classic experiment by }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-6 Henry and Rogers (1960). They demonstrated that for}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5  a ballistic task, which requires both fast RT and fast movement, RT increases as a function of the number of component parts of the required \u173 ?
action. Numerous other experiments have confirmed these findings (e.g., Anson, 1982; Christina & Rose, }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-6
1985; Fischman, 1984). From a preparation-of-\u173 ?action}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5  perspective, these results indicate that the }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 complexity of the \u173 ?action to be performed influences the amount of time a person requires to \u173 ?
prepare the motor control system}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 .\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 A question arose from these experiments related to whether, in fact, the key factor is the number of\u8239 ?
component parts involved in the action. Because the amount of time to perform the action and the number of component parts of the action are confounded when actions of different complexity are compared, it is possible that the amount of time \u173 ?
required may be the cause of the RT increase. To \u173 ?investigate which of these two factors influenced RT in the Henry and Rogers\rquote  experiment, Christina and colleagues carried out a series of experiments that provided support for the Henry and Rogers\rquote  conclusion that the number of component parts is the key in the RT increase (for a review of this \u173 ?
research, see Christina, 1992).\par }\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Movement Accuracy\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i As the accuracy demands for a movement increase, }{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd2\expndtw10 the amount of preparation time required also }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 increases.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  Researchers have nicely demonstrated }{\fs20 this effect in comparisons of RTs for manual aiming tasks that differed according to the target sizes. }
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 For example, Sidaway, Sekiya, and Fairweather }{\fs20 (1995) had people perform manual aiming tasks in which they had to hit two targets in sequence as quickly as\u8239 ?
possible. Two results showed the influence on preparation of the accuracy demands of the task. First, RT increased as target size decreased. Second, when the first target was a constant size, the dispersion of the location of hits on that target was\u8239 ?
related to the size of the second target. These results have been replicated by additional research (e.g., Fischman, Yao, & Reeve, 2000).\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 An important aspect of this research is that it \u173 ?extends our understanding of Fitts\rquote  law, which we discussed in chapter 7. Fitts}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \rquote  law concerns the increase in}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 movement time associated with the accuracy demands of a movement, regardless of movement complexity. The research we have discussed here by Sidaway and others shows that the increase in accuracy demands also increases the amount of time needed to }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 prepare}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  to move. The need }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1
fo}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 r additional time for action preparation in these situations is likely due to the additional preparation required for a person to constrain his or her limb to move within spatial constraints imposed by the smaller target. (See Kourtis, Sebanz, & Knoblich, 2012, for a study that shows the }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 electrophysiological}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1  correlates of Fitts\rquote  law during action planning.)\par }
\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 The Repetition of a Movement}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 A well-known characteristic of human performance is that when the performance situation requires a person to repeat the same response on the next \u173 ?
attempt, that person\rquote s RT for the next trial will be faster than it was for the previous attempt. As the number of trials increases, the influence of the repetitions on RT lessens. Again, as in other perfor\u173 ?}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 mance situations, the decrease in preparation time is }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 due to a reduction in the response-selection process (see Campbell & Proctor, 1993).}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \par }\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 The Time between Different Responses\line to Different Signals\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 There are some performance situations that require a person to respond to a signal with one action and then very quickly respond to another signal with a different action. For example, when a basketball player is confronted by a defensive player in a one-on-one situation, he or she might fake a move in\u8239 ?
one direction (the first signal) before moving in the opposite direction (the second signal). Each \ldblquote signal\rdblquote  by the offensive player requires the defensive player to initiate a movement. In this situation, }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i RT will be slower for the defensive player\rquote s second movement than for his or her first.}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The RT delay for the second movement is due to\u8239 ?the }{\*\cs63\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 psychological refractory period (PRP)}
{\fs20 , which can be thought of as a delay period (the term }{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i refractory}{\fs20  is synonymous with }{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i
delay}{\fs20 ) during which a person cannot select the second movement until after he or she selects and initiates the first. As such, the }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i PRP reflects a distinct limitation in the action preparation process.}{\fs20 \par Figure 8.3 illustrates the PRP using the basketball one-on-one situation described earlier. The player with the ball (Player A) fakes a move to the left but then quickly moves to the right. He or she gains extra time to carry out the move to the right because of the RT delay created by the PRP that \u173 ?
results from Player B\rquote s initial reaction to the fake. The illustration shows that Player B\rquote s RT would b}{\fs20 e t}
{\fs20 he same amount of time for Player A}{\fs20 \rquote s move to the right if it had not been preceded by a fake move to the left. But the fake requires Player B to initiate a response to the fake before he or she can initiate a response to the move to the right.\par The first evidence of the PRP was published in 1931 by Telford. Since that time, the delay has been demonstrated by numerous researchers and in a \u173 ?
variety of settings (for a review of this research, see Lien & Proctor, 2002). Although researchers continue to seek an appropriate theoretical explanation for the PRP, there is general consensus that the \u173 ?
delay in responding to the second stimulus is related to the }{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 response selection}{\fs20  demands of the two S-R tasks that must be performed in rapid succession}
{\fs20  or to the timing of response initiation (Klapp, Maslovat, & Jagacinski, 2018)}{\fs20 . The response to the second stimulus waits for the completion of the response to the first stimulus. In fact, the PRP can be eliminated if the second stimulus occurs after the response to the first stimulus. The theoretical issue concerns why the second response must wait until the completion of the first response. We will consider this issue in chapter 9.\par }
\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb380\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Performer Characteristics Influencing Preparation}{\fs21 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd2\expndtw8 In addition to task and situation characteris}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 tics, certain characteristics of the performer also influence the process of action preparation. We should think of these characteristics as situational, because they refer to the state of the person at the time a skill must be performed. It is important to note here that these performer characteristics typically influence not only the time needed to prepare a voluntary movement but also the quality of its performance.\par }
\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb250\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Alertness of the Performer\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 An important principle of human performance is that the alertness of the performer influences the time he or she takes to prepare a required action, as well as the quality of the action itself. In two types of performance situations, the role of alertness is \u173 ?
especially critical. One type is the RT task, where a person does not have to wait for any length of time beyond a few seconds, but must \u173 ?
respond to a stimulus as quickly and as accurately as possible. The other type, involving the long-term maintenance of alertness, is the task for which fast and \u173 ?
accurate responding is \u173 ?important, but the signals to which the person must respond occur infrequently and irregularly.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 For RT tasks, a way to increase the likelihood that a person is optimally alert and prepared to \u173 ?respond appropriately is to provide some type of }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw1 warning signal}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1  that indicates he or she must respond within the next few seconds. Researchers demonstrated the benefit of this warning signal more than a century ago, in the early days of human performance research. In fact, there was sufficient evidence accumulated in the first half of the 1900s to conclude that RT is significantly faster when a warning signal precedes the signal to respond than when there is no warning signal (Teichner, 1954).}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 \par }{\fs20 An important point is that after the warning signal, there is an optimal length of time for the person to develop and maintain alertness while waiting for the go signal. If the go signal occurs too soon after the warning signal, or if the person must wait too long, RT will be longer than if the go signal occurs sometime between these two points in time. These performance effects indicate that people require a minimum amount of time to develop optimal alertness and that we can maintain that level of alertness for a limited amount of time.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 As you can see in figure 8.4, there is an optimal time range during which the go signal should occur following the warning signal. The exact amounts of time to insert in this figure will depend on the skill and situation. However, for simple-RT situations, a reasonable guideline is this: }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 The optimal fore\u173 ?period length should range between 1 and 4 sec.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0
\par }\pard\plain \s17\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs66\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd-1\expndtw-3\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Vigilance.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3
\u8194\'20The long-term maintenance of alertness is known as }{\*\cs63\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 vigilance}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  In vigilance situations, an individual must perform an appropriate action when he or she detects a signal to act. The problem is that }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd1\expndtw5 signals occur very infrequently and irregularly.}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw5  }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4
There }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 are many vigilance situations in motor skill performance}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  contexts. In sports, a situation involving vigilance occurs when baseball outfielder}
{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-4 s}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  must maintain alertness throughout an inning in the\u8239 ?field despite having only one ball hit }
{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-4 their}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  way, out of the many pitches thrown. In industry, workers who must detect and remove defective products from the assembly line will see many products move past }
{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-4 them}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  for long periods of time, but only a few will be\u8239 ?}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4
defective. Similarly, driving a car or track along an uncrowded freeway is a vigilance task when a person drives for an extended time. Lifeguarding at a pool or beach can be a vigilance problem because situations requiring a response are very infrequent}
{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-4  during a long shift on duty}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 . Medical personnel often are required to work long hours and still be able to identify symptoms of health problems correctly and perform surgical techniques \u173 ?
requiring precise motor control.\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 In each of these situations, RT increases as a function of the amount of time the person must maintain alertness to detect certain signals. Detection errors increase as well. Scientists first reported this phenomenon during World War II (see Mackworth, 1956). In experiments investigating the detection of signals simulating those observed on a radar screen, results showed that both the RT to a signal and the accuracy of detecting signals deteriorated markedly with each half hour during a two-hour work interval.\par }
{\fs20 Although performance in vigilance situations \u173 ?deteriorates the longer a person needs to remain \u173 ?attentive to the possibility of needing to detect a signal and make a response, lack of sufficient sleep makes vigilance performance even worse. Research has consistently demonstrated that sleep deprivation (i.e., lack of sleep for extended periods of time), \u173 ?
insufficient sleep (i.e., sleeping for fewer hours at night than needed), and sleep disruption negatively impact a person\rquote s performance in vigilance situations (see for example, Dinges et al., \line }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 1997; Drummond et al., 2005). There is general agreement that the best way to overcome sleep-\u173 ?related performance problems is to sleep. However, this option is not always possible, which has led researchers to investigate various stimulants as alternative ways to provide short-term enhancement }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 of performance (e.g., Magill et al., 2003; Wesensten,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  Killgore, }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
& Balkin, 2005).\par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Eason, Beardshall, and Jaffee (1965) nicely demonstrated that alertness deterioration contributes to the performance decrements associated with long-term vigilance. They provided physiological evidence consistent with decreases in vigilance performance over one-hour sessions. Skin conduc-tance in participants decreased, indicating increased calming and drowsiness over the session. In addition, participants\rquote  neck tension steadily \u173 ?
increased, as their nervous systems attempted to compensate by increasing muscle activity in the neck.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }
\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Attention Focused on the Signal versus \line the Movement\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Many motor skills, such as sprints in track and swimming, require a person to move as fast as \u173 ?possible when the signal to move occurs. In these situations, there are two important components, the RT and the movement time (MT). To prepare to \u173 ?
initiate his or her movement, the person can focus on the signal itself (a }{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i sensory set}{\fs20 ) or on the movement required (a }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i motor set}{\fs20 ). Research evidence, first \u173 ?provided by Franklin Henry (1960), indicates that which of the two components the performer consciously focuses attention on influences RT.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 However, because Henry\rquote s results were based on the participants\rquote  opinions of what their sets were, Christina (1973) imposed on each participant either a sensory or a motor set to initiate a fast arm \u173 ?
movement. The sensory-set group was told to focus attention on the sound of the go signal, a buzzer, but to move off the response key as fast as possible. The motor-set group was told to focus on moving as\u8239 ?
quickly as possible. Results showed that the \u173 ?sensory-set group had an RT 20 msec faster than that of the motor-set group. Interestingly, MT was not statistically different for the two groups. Thus, participants\rquote  focusing of attention on the signal and \u173 ?
allowing the movement to happen naturally shortened the preparation time required and did not \u173 ?penalize movement speed, yielding a faster overall response time.}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \par }{\fs20 Jongsma, Elliott, and Lee (1987) replicated these laboratory results in a sport performance situation. They compared sensory and motor sets for a sprint start in track. To measure RT, the authors embedded a pressure-sensitive switch in the rear-foot starting block. They measured MT as the time from the release of this switch until a photoelectric light beam was broken 1.5 m from the starting line. Results showed that for both novices and experienced sprinters, RT was faster for the sensory-set condition.\par }
\pard\plain \s15\f5\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21\expnd0\expndtw-2 WHAT OCCURS DURING \line PREPARATION?}{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 On the basis of the discussion so far, you can see that the process of preparing an action is complex. It includes perceptual, cognitive, and motor components. One way to demonstrate that the preparation process includes these components is to divide an EMG recording of the RT interval into components by \u173 ?
using a technique known as }{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i fractionating RT,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  which was introduced in chapter 2.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
\par }\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Evidence from Fractionating RT\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 As we described in chapter 2, to fractionate RT, the EMG recording taken from the agonist muscle involved in a movement is divided into two distinct components (see figure 2.3). The first is the \line }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i premotor}{\fs20  component (sometimes referred to as electromechanical delay). The EMG signal does not change much from what it was prior to the onset of the signal. However, shortly after the onset of the signal, the EMG signal shows a rapid increase in electrical activity. This \u173 ?
indicates that the motor neurons are firing and the muscle is preparing to contract, even though no observable movement has yet occurred. In this period of time, the }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i motor}{\fs20  component is the increased EMG activity preceding the observable movement.\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 The premotor and motor components of RT represent two distinct activities that occur prior to \u173 ?observable movement and reflect different types of movement preparation processes. The premotor component includes the perceptual or cognitive processing of the stimulus information and preparing \line the movement features of the required action. The motor component begins the actual motor output phase of a movement. During this time, the specific muscles involved in the action are firing and preparing to begin to produce observable movement.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 By fractionating RT, we can gain insight into what occurs during the action preparation process. \u173 ?
Researchers look at which of these RT components is influenced by the various factors we discussed earlier that influence RT. For example, Christina \line }
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw7 and Rose (1985) reported that the changes in }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 RT due to increases in }{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2
response complexity}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  were reflected in increases in the premotor component. For a two-part arm movement, the premotor component increased an average of 19 msec over that for a one-part arm movement, whereas the motor component increased only 3 msec. Siegel (1986) found that RT increased linearly as }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 movement \line durations}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  increased from 150, through 300 and 600, to 1,200 msec, the length of the premotor component also increased linearly. The motor component, on the other hand, remained the same length until the response duration became 1,200 msec; then it showed a slight increase. Sheridan (1984) showed that the premotor component was also responsible for RT increases due to increases in }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 movement velocity}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 . However, Carlton, Carlton, and Newell (1987) found changes in both the premotor and motor components by altering }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 force-related characteristics}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  of the re}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 sponse. Similar changes in both premotor and motor}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  components were reported by Davranche, Burle, Audiffren, and Hasbroucq (2005) in their investigation of the basis for the improvement in choice-RT performance that occurs while }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 performing a submaximal exercise}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 .\par }\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Postural Preparation\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 This postural preparation process is commonly referred to as }{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 anticipatory postural adjustments.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  The term \ldblquote anticipatory\rdblquote  indicates that prior to the execution of an intended action or movement, \line there are additional muscles that activate, a process that occurs nonconsciously. Researchers typically use EMG recordings to investigate these muscular activities. The demonstration of anticipatory postural adjustments presents further support for the complexity and sophistication of the motor control system. Although numerous experiments have been reported that provide evidence for the postural preparation activities that precede the initiation of an intended action, we will consider only a few examples. These examples include actions that involve simple and complex limb movements as well as whole-body movements. These research examples show us that all of the actions we perform, even those involving the simplest of movements, require a complex synergistic system of muscles to work together.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Weeks and Wallace (1992) asked people to per}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 form an elbow-flexion aiming movement in the }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 horizontal plane while standing in an erect posture. Participants learned to make this movement in three different \u173 ?
velocities defined by criterion movement }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw7 times. The authors made EMG recordings from }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
various muscles of both legs and the responding arm. The \u173 ?results showed that a specific sequence of supporting postural events occurred. For each movement \u173 ?
velocity, the muscles of the contralateral and ipsilateral legs (biceps femoris and rectus femoris) activated }{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i
prior to}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  the onset of the arm agonist muscles (biceps brachii). And as the arm velocity increased, the onset of the anticipatory postural muscle activity occurred at an earlier time prior to arm agonist \u173 ?
muscle activation. The authors also found different onset orders for the various postural muscles.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 More recently, Bonnetblanc, Martin, and }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3\u173 ?}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Teasdale }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \line }{\fs20 (2004) found that for an arm-pointing movement at different-sized targets (5, 10, and 25 cm wide) while standing, leg muscles not only activated before the arm began to move (similar to what Weeks and \u173 ?
Wallace found), but the amount of activation of specific muscles also varied according to the size of the target. For example, as target size decreased, EMG activity increased in the erector spinae but decreased in the tibialis \u173 ?
anterior and the rectus femoris of the quadriceps. When considered in relation to Fitts\rquote  law, which we discussed in chapter 7, these \u173 ?
results suggest that the relationship between movement time and movement accuracy demands has a basis in the preparation of the movements. In addition, these results provide \u173 ?
evidence of muscle preparation differences associated with the relationship between RT and movement accuracy as reported by Sidaway and others, which we considered earlier in this chapter.\par }
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw5 Postural preparation effects have also been }{\fs20 shown for leg movements. For example, in a study by Mercer and Sahrmann (1999), people of three }
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3 age groups (8\'d012, 25\'d035, and 65}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3 \'d073 }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3 years}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3
), who \line }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw6 had no neuromuscular impairments, performed }{\fs20 two types of stair-stepping movements: stepping onto a stair step with one foot \u173 ?
(the \ldblquote place task\rdblquote ) and stepping onto a stair step with one\u8239 ?foot and then putting the other foot on the step \u173 ?
(the \ldblquote step task\rdblquote ). The experimenters analyzed EMG recordings from four muscles of the stance leg }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1\u173 ?
(tibialis anterior, gastrocnemius-soleus, hamstring,}{\fs20  and gluteus maximus) and two muscles of the \u173 ?moving leg (rectus femoris and gluteus maximus). When the experimenters analyzed the EMG results in terms of the onset (i.e., activation) times for each muscle for all participants, they found that the \u173 ?
tibialis anterior (TA) of the stance leg was the first }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 muscle to activate. On average, it activated 215 msec}
{\fs20  }{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i before}{\fs20  the initiation of movement by the opposite leg for the stepping task and 307 msec }{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i
before}{\fs20  movement initiation for the place tasks. This initial activation of the TA in the stance leg ensured postural stability when the opposite leg stepped forward. Another important result of this experiment is the variety of muscle activation sequences demonstrated by each participant and across the participants for each task. Figure 8.5 shows the \u173 ?
specific muscle activation sequences exhibited for\u8239 ?the two tasks and the number of participants in}{\fs20\u8239 ?each age group who displayed each sequence on at least\u8239 ?
75 percent of the trials (which the experi}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 menters \u173 ?referred to as representative of a \ldblquote preferred\rdblquote }
{\fs20  \u173 ?sequence). These results demonstrate that no specific sequence of muscle activation characterized all or any one of the participants for either task.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 Finally, would you expect anticipatory postural adjustments to precede a simple movement like tapping your index finger on a tabletop while sitting in a chair? Two researchers in Italy (C}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 aronni & Cav}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 allari, 2009) reported that prior to the activation of the prime mover muscles for this tapping activity (i.e., the flexor digitorum superficialis) several upper-limb and upper-back muscles activated in specific sequences that served to stabilize the upper limb during the finger tapping movements.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 The sequences of muscle activation reported in these experiments demonstrate that the preparation of postural stability is an important part of action preparation. The experiments show that }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 postural preparation involves organizing a flexibly orga\u173 ?nized synergy}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2
 of muscles. This conclusion is important because movement scientists traditionally have assumed that postural muscle preparation is rigidly temporally organized. The advantage of the flexibly organized synergy is that anticipatory postural activity can occur according to the person\rquote s equilibrium needs for specific situations.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \par }\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Preparation of Limb Movement \line Characteristics\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 An essential part of the action preparation process is selecting and organizing the specific movement characteristics of the limbs to perform according to the dictates of task constraints and characteristics. Because an individual often can perform the same action using several different limbs or different segments of the same limb, he or she must specify and prepare the limb or limb segments to be involved in performing a given task.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 One feature of limb movement a person must prepare is the }{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 direction}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0
 or directions in which the limbs must move. For a very rapid movement, a person may prepare several different directions before initiating the movement. Another feature related to direction preparation is the }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 trajectory}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  the }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 limb}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  will follow during movement. For a task requiring a ballistic movement and spatial accuracy, an individual must prepare in advance, constraining the limb movement to meet the accuracy constraints of the task. In addition, as we discussed in chapter 7, a person catching a ball must prepare his or her hand and finger movements before the oncoming ball reaches him or her.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \par }\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Preparation of Movements for Object Control\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 When the action to be performed involves manipulating an object, a part of the preparation process involves specifying certain movement features needed to control the object. The following are two of those features involved in this aspect of movement preparation.\par }
\pard\plain \s17\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs66\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw-1\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Force control.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
\u8194\'20An important movement feature prepared prior to manipulating an object is setting the amount of force required to lift or move the \u173 ?
object. As an illustration of this type of preparation, think about situations in which you have looked at an object and, because of certain characteristics, judged it to be heavy. But when you began to lift it, you discovered it was light. Undoubtedly, you lifted the object much more quickly and higher in the air than you had intended. Why did you respond in this way? The reason is that because of certain obser\u173 ?}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 vable characteristics of the object, such as a beverage}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  can that looks unopened although it is actually empty, you anticipated that a certain amount of \u173 ?
muscular force would be required to lift the object. This anticipated amount of force was used to \u173 ?}{\f6\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1
prepare}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  the musculature for the lifting action.\par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Researchers have used this common everyday experience to provide evidence that the movement force characteristics are prepared in advance of the manipulation of objects. For example, Butler et al. (1993) showed that when men did not know the weight of a box that looked like it was filled with heavy objects, they performed with a jerking motion. Movement kinematics of these lifts showed that velocities at the shoulders and knees were much higher than the velocities when the men knew the actual weight of the box. In a }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 similar }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 type of study, researchers in The Netherlands (van der Burgh, van Die}{\*\cs68\f9\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1
\'91}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 n, & Toussaint, 2000) found that when healthy male participants were asked to pick up and lift a box as quickly as possible, an unexpected increase of 5 or 10 kg of weight resulted }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 in }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 their initially activating low-back muscles similar to when they had lifted the lighter, no-added}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 -}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 weight box, which indicated that no force control adjustment was made prior to the initial lift of the box with the increased weight. Supporting this point was the finding that just prior to the grasp and initial lift of the box, muscle activity didn\rquote t differ for the increased and no-added}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 -}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 weight boxes, which indicated similar force control preparation activity.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Another example of the preparation of force control can be seen in handwriting. To prepare to write with a pen, a person needs to specify the amount of grip force on the pen as well as the amount of pressure to apply on the writing surface. Research (e.g., Wann }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 & Nimmo-Smith, 1991) has shown that experienced writers adjust the amount of pen pressure on the writing surface according to the characteristics of the surface to allow energy-efficient, continuous, \u173 ?
fluent motion. In contrast, children with handwriting problems often grip the pen with excessive force and use excessive pen pressure on the writing surface.\par }
\pard\plain \s17\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb260\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs66\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw-1\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 End-state comfort control.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 When you reach to grasp an object that you plan to do something with, how do you position your hand to grasp the object? According to an increasing amount of research, we grasp objects based on what we plan to do with them. This means that when we grasp the object our hand position is based on the position that will feel the most comfortable to complete the action\'d1do what we intended to do with the object. For example, if you want to pick up a cup that is upside down on a table so that you can fill the cup with water, you will probably pick up the cup with the grip that will be most comfortable when you place the cup upright in order to fill it, even if this grip feels rather awkward when you initially grasp the cup.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 The typically spontaneous grasp position based on the final position of the hand when the object is used in its intended way is a phenomenon known as the end-state}
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3  comfort effect.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  Stated simply, this effect is \ldblquote the tendency to take hold of an object in an awkward posture to permit a more comfortable, or more easily controlled, final posture once the object is brought to its target position\rdblquote  (Zhang & Rosenbaum, 2008, }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \line }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 p. 383). The significance of the end-state comfort effect is that it demonstrates an important feature of object control that is part of the action preparation process. This feature involves the planning of the final hand posture that will be the most comfortable or easiest to control. }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Several studies have reported support for this effect since it was first reported by Rosenbaum and }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3\u173 ?}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Jorgenson (1992) (for reviews of this research, see Fischman, Stodden, & Lehman, 2003; Rosenbaum, Cohen, Meulenbroek,}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 & Vaughan, 2006). Results from a series of experiments by \u173 ?Cohen and }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3\u173 ?}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Rosenbaum (2004) indicate that the preparation of hand posture in this way demonstrates that the preparation process for prehension actions involves planning that is based on the generation of a new plan or the recall of an action that was successfully used in similar situations in the past.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Of the several hypotheses proposed to explain the end-state comfort effect, one that continues to gain support is the precision hypothesis (e.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 g., }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Herbort}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  & Kunde, 2019;}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  Rosenbaum, van Heutgen, }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 & Caldwell, 1996; Short & Cauraugh, 1999). This explanation proposes that precision in limb positioning will be greater, the movement will be faster, }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 and control over the object will be better}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  when a person\rquote s limb is in a comfortable position. Thus, to ensure a faster and more accurate final limb and \u173 ?
object position, a person prepares movement characteristics according to the comfort of the final rather than the starting position of the limb. Although this strategy may require some awkward hand and arm postures when picking up an object, it enables the person to more effectively and efficiently achieve the object manipulation goal. Interestingly, people will choose their non-dominant hand over their dominant hand to perform a task if the end-state comfort will be higher for their non-dominant hand (Coelho, Studenka, & Rosenba}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 um, 2}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 014).}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb260\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Preparation of Sequences of Movements\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Playing}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  the piano, typing on a keyboard}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 , and speaking}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
 are examples of skills that involve the sequencing of series of movements. Two types of research evidence indicate that short sequences of these movements are prepared in advance of the initial movement. One is the systematic increase in RT as movement complexity increases, which we discussed earlier in this chapter. The other evidence is }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 that the kinematic characteristics of hand and finger movements during typing and piano playing and the lips, tongue, and jaw during speaking are modified by what elements in the sequence of movements come before or after them.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  (e.g., \u173 ?Engel, Flander}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 s, &}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  Soechting, 1997; Soechting & Flanders, 1992). For example, in the Engel et al. study, skilled pianists played short \u173 ?
excerpts from three }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 piano }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 pieces }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 that each contained two phrases. The first few notes were played identically with the right hand, but after that point the notes were played differently.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  In one piece, the first four notes }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 ascended and the next two notes descended. Pianists typically play the first note in this phrase with the thumb, the next note with the index finger, and continue until the fourth note is played with the ring finger. As the phrase descends, the pianists use the same fingers in reverse order. In a second version of the phrase, the first four notes ascended, as before, but the next two notes continued to ascend. Pianists will now reposition the hand after the third note so that the fourth note is played with the thumb and the remaining two notes are played with the index finger followed by the middle finger.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Two aspects of the results provided evidence for movement preparation in advance. First, the high consistency of the timing of key depresses and releases and the hand and finger kinematics within each pianist suggested advance preparation. Second, the timings and movement kinematics of the phrase that descended were different from those when the phrase continued to ascend and the differences were apparent from as early as the second note onward. So, even though the first three notes were identical and were played with the same fingers, their timings and kinematics were modified for the second variation of the phrase in anticipation of repositioning the hand so that the fourth note could be played with the thumb. In other words, the first few notes of the two phrases were prepared in distinct ways even though these notes were identical and were played with the same fingers.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 In light of these sequential movement preparation characteristics, it\rquote s worth noting that slower performance is not always due only to preparation processes. For example, a common characteristic of people with Parkinson\rquote s disease (PD) is moving slowly when performing a movement sequence. In a study by Smiley-Oyen, Kerr, and Lowry (2007), an analysis of adults with PD performing sequential manual aiming movements to 1, 3, 5, and 7 \u173 ?
targets showed that the slow movement speed (i.e., bradykinesia) was due to both movement planning and execution strategies.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4
\par }\pard\plain \s16\f5\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb260\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Rhythmicity Preparation\par }\pard\plain \s13\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Many skills require that the component movements follow specific rhythmic patterns. We can see this characteristic in any of the various types of gait, performance of a dance sequence, shooting \line of a free throw in basketball, and so on. In some of these activities, the participant can take time before \u173 ?
performing it to engage in some preperformance \u173 ?activities that are commonly referred to as rituals. \u173 ?Interestingly, rhythmic patterns also characterize preperformance rituals and appear to influence performance. Although this relationship has not been widely studied, the few research studies investigating it have consistently shown a positive correlation between the rhythm of the preperformance routine }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 and the success of the performance itself (e.g., \u173 ?\line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Jackson, 2003; }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
Southard & Amos, 1996; Southard & Miracle, 1993; Wrisberg & Pein, 1992). In terms of the preparation of action, the preperformance \u173 ?
rituals would appear to stabilize the motor control system and \u173 ?orient it to engaging in a rhythmic \u173 ?activity.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 The Southard and Amos (1996) study will serve as a good example of how these researchers have determined that such a relationship exists. They video-recorded fifteen basketball free throws, golf putts, and tennis serves for experienced university men who had established rituals for each of these activities. Each video recording was analyzed to determine the preperformance behaviors each participant used on each trial. The types of behaviors for each activity are listed in table 8.1. It is important to note that although each of the behaviors was observed, individual participants did not exhibit every behavior. The researchers also analyzed the total time to perform the ritual and the relative time for each behavior in the ritual, which was the percentage of time engaged in each behavior in the ritual. Results showed a moderately high .77 correlation between the relative time for the ritual behaviors and successful performance. This relationship suggests that the consistent relative timing of preperformance ritual behaviors may be an important part of the successful performance of closed motor skills that provide an opportunity for the performer to engage in preperformance rituals.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \par }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 Mack (2001) provided additional evidence that the consistent performance of the components of a preperformance routine is more important than the total amount of time taken to perform the routine. Although he did not assess the relative time of the\u8239 ?
components of a routine, he compared the influence of altering a normal routine in terms of its \u173 ?duration and component activities. He found essentially no influence on the free-throw shooting \u173 ?
performance of university basketball players when they had to double the amount of time they normally took for their pre-shot routine, but a decrease in performance when they had to include some new activities in their normal routine.\par }
{\fs20 In a study by Cotterill, Sanders, and Collins (2010), elite golfers in England (handicap range of 0\'d02) were interviewed about their preperformance routines. Two results are especially relevant to our discussion. First, the use of rhythm was commonly indicated as part of the routine. For example, one golfer stated that prior to a shot, \ldblquote I then step in, and set up and one-two, I just think one-two, one-two, the words occupy my mind, while the rhythm is timed for my back swing and forward swing\rdblquote  (p. 56). Second, the interviews indicated not only the individual differences of the routines used, but also the consistency within the individual golfers in their use of the routines. A subsequent study showed that elite golfers had developed different routines for different types of shots (Cotterill, }
{\fs20 Collins}{\fs20 , & Sanders, 2014).}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s18\f5\fs18\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li120\ri0\sb0\sa250\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs18 Summary\par }\pard\plain \s19\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 To perform a motor skill, a person prepares the motor control system just prior to performing the skill.\par }
\pard\plain \s20\f6\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb140\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The preparation process requires time, which is commonly measured by reaction time (RT); the amount of time required depends on a variety of task, situation, and personal characteristics. When used in this way, RT is an index of the preparation time needed to perform a skill.\par }
{\*\cs61\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 Task and situation characteristics}{\fs20  that influence the amount of time required to prepare an action include:}
