{\fs20 the number of movement response alternatives (i.e., choices) in the situation from which the performer must choose only one; Hick\rquote s law describes the relationship between RT and the number of choices.}
{\fs20 \par the predictability of the correct movement \u173 ?response alternative when there are several from which to choose\par }
{\fs20 the probability of precue correctness\par the degree of stimulus-response compatibility}{\fs20 \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
the regularity of the length of the RT foreperiod}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }{\fs20 movement complexity\par }{\fs20 movement accuracy demands\par the amount of movement response repetition involved in a situation}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s22\f6\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi-200\li370\ri0\sb60\sa60\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 the amount of time available between different movement responses; when the time \u173 ?between two responses is short, the psychological refractory period (PRP) will influence the initiation of the second response}
