{\fs18 The study of reaction time (RT) as an indicator of mental operations has a history that can be traced back to the middle of the nineteenth century. Scientists were becoming interested in determining the \u173 ?
basic elements of thought. The investigation of RT provided a useful means of investigating this question because it represented the time interval between the detection of a stimulus and the initiation of a response to it. Dr. F. C. Donders, a Dutch physician, hypothesized that specific mental operations occur in a \u173 ?
specific series of stages during the RT interval and was certain that he could identify each stage. He initiated research that was published in 1868 (Donders, 1868\'d01969) and continues to influence researchers \u173 ?
today. To test his hypothesis, he set up three different \ldblquote methods\rdblquote  for performing reaction-time tasks.}{\fs18
\par }\pard\plain \s36\f6\fs18\ltrpar\ql\fi-155\li155\ri0\sb0\sa0\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
