{\fs19 Achieving a Standing Posture from Various Sitting Postures: An Example of How Functional Demands Affect Action Preparation\par }
\pard\plain \s51\f6\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18 Changing from a sitting posture to a standing posture (referred to as a sit-to-stand action) is a common everyday activity that provides a good example of how the motor control system adapts to allow the same action to occur from a variety of initial postural positions. Shepherd and Gentile (1994) presented evidence of this adaptability by having healthy adults sit in different postures on a chair (an erect trunk, a fully flexed trunk, and a partially flexed trunk, i.e., flexed between the fully flexed and erect positions), and then stand. Analyses of the various joint movements involved in this action showed this:\par }
\pard\plain \s52\f6\fs18\ltrpar\ql\fi-155\li155\ri0\sb0\sa0\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\f4\fs18\b0\i In the erect and partially flexed sitting postures:}{\fs18  The knee began to extend before the hip joint \u173 ?
began to extend.\par }{\f4\fs18\b0\i In the fully flexed sitting posture:}{\fs18  the hip \line joint \u173 ?began to extend before the knee began to extend.\par }
\pard\plain \s51\f6\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18 These different initiation patterns of joint movements illustrate how functional demands influence the order of muscle activation in preparing an action. Because different sitting postures will require different support, propulsion, and balance characteristics during the sit-to-stand action, the order of the initiation of movement of the knee or hip joints is a critical factor in enabling a person to carry out the intended action without losing balance.\par }
