{\fs19 Performance Expectations as Part of Action Preparation\par }\pard\plain \s35\f6\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18 Often overlooked in the study of motor learning and control is the role of motivation to perform a skill. A motivational variable known as }
{\*\cs61\fs18\b0\i performance expectancies,}{\fs18  which refers to a performer\rquote s expectations of how he or she will perform a skill, is particularly relevant to the action preparation process. A study by Stoate, Wulf, and Lewthwaite (2012) presents a notable example of the influence of a performer\rquote s expectancies on the person\rquote s quality of performance, with particular emphasis on the efficiency of that performance (with the term }
{\*\cs61\fs18\b0\i efficiency}{\fs18  referring to the amount of energy used to perform a skill, i.e., lower energy use indicates higher efficiency). In addition to presenting an experiment designed to test their performance expectancy effect hypothesis, the authors also provide an excellent review of research describing the motivational effects of various forms of influencing expectancies for both novice and skilled performers. }
{\fs18 It is important to note here that this same performance expectancy phenomenon was discussed as an essential part of the OPTIMAL theory of motor learning, which we discussed in chapter 5.}
